        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>, which was published 24 February 1871 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The enclosure was presumably a copy of CD’s Queries about expression (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, Appendix VII). Question 13 was: ‘When a man wishes to shew that he cannot prevent something being done, does he shrug his shoulders, turn inwards his elbows, extend outward his hands and open the palms; with the eyebrows raised.’ <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_623.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Laura Dewey Bridgman</ref> is thought to have been the first blind, deaf, and mute person to receive a formal academic education (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_152.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">ANB</hi></ref>). CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6171.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Lieber</ref> and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4748.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Lieber 1851</ref>, p. 7.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD discussed the development of the intellectual and moral faculties in humans in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 158–84.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1960.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Jane Loring Gray</ref> and to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 17, letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1957.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Asa Gray</ref> and J. L. Gray, 8 and 9 May 1869 and nn. 5, 7, 9, 10, 12, and 13.</note>
        </div>        
            
